---
import Layout from '../../../components/layout/Layout.astro';
import ArtworkSchema from '../../../components/seo/ArtworkSchema.astro';

const lang = 'en' as const;
const title = 'La travesia';

const img1 = (await import('../../../assets/images/obras/la-travesia/la-travesia-01.webp')).default;
const img2 = (await import('../../../assets/images/obras/la-travesia/la-travesia-02.webp')).default;
const img3 = (await import('../../../assets/images/obras/la-travesia/la-travesia-03.webp')).default;
const img4 = (await import('../../../assets/images/obras/la-travesia/la-travesia-04.webp')).default;
const img5 = (await import('../../../assets/images/obras/la-travesia/la-travesia-05.webp')).default;
---

<Layout
  lang={lang}
  title="La travesia — Work"
  description="La travesia (2017–2024). Installation — used and discarded wooden doors from family homes and mirror. MAMU, Bogota. Maria Elvira Escallon."
>

  <ArtworkSchema
    title="La travesia"
    year="2017–2024"
    medium="Installation. Used and discarded wooden doors from family homes and mirror"
    dimensions="2.40 x 15 x 1.80 m"
    description="Doors from demolished homes arranged as a corridor. A mirror at the end creates an infinite reflection of these thresholds. MAMU, Bogota, 2024."
    url="https://mariaelviraescallon.com/en/works/la-travesia/"
  />

  <article class="work-page">
    <div class="container">

      <!-- Header -->
      <header class="work-page__header">
        <p class="label">Work / 022</p>
        <h1>{title}</h1>
        <p class="work-page__meta">2017–2024 &nbsp;/&nbsp; Installation — used and discarded wooden doors, mirror &nbsp;/&nbsp; 2.40 x 15 x 1.80 m</p>
      </header>

      <!-- Main gallery -->
      <div class="work-page__gallery">
        <img src={img1.src} alt="La travesia — Corridor of doors from demolished homes, frontal view" loading="eager">
        <img src={img2.src} alt="La travesia — Infinite reflection in the mirror at the end of the door corridor" loading="lazy">
        <img src={img3.src} alt="La travesia — Detail of salvaged doors" loading="lazy">
        <img src={img4.src} alt="La travesia — Side view of the door corridor" loading="lazy">
        <img src={img5.src} alt="La travesia — Installation at MAMU" loading="lazy">
      </div>

      <!-- Text + Technical sheet -->
      <div class="work-page__body">
        <div class="work-page__text">

          <p class="curatorial">
            The installation is composed of three parts, made in different media. The journey begins with the following phrase from the Iliad: "Y dejando las armas en el fertil suelo se pararon muy cerca los unos de los otros" [Translation: And leaving their weapons on the fertile ground, they stood very close to one another]. The project alludes to the difficult path of return toward peace by the actors of the conflict, after having lived decades of armed confrontation.
          </p>

          <p class="curatorial" style="margin-top: var(--s2);">
            First part. Thresholds Installation. The viewer must walk through a narrow, long, claustrophobic space. On each side of this passage, we find numerous doors leaning against the walls. They are quite worn doors that have been extracted from demolished family homes. Toward the end of the corridor, there is the only door that can be opened.
          </p>

          <p class="curatorial" style="margin-top: var(--s2);">
            Second part. Video installation. A set of scenes is presented where a blind person carries on their back a person who lacks a leg, traversing a territory that is sometimes deserted, sometimes hostile. Supported by their mutual limitations and possibilities, they manage to advance with difficulty, slowly recognizing one another. The scenes do not follow a script; rather, they propose an emotional and sensory atmosphere. Wall with found historical images on the theme of the blind and the crippled.
          </p>

          <p class="curatorial" style="margin-top: var(--s2);">
            Third part. In a third room, a video presents a domestic scene: the laundry sink of a country house, behind which there is a window overlooking the countryside. In front of the window, on the clothesline, three garments dry in the wind and suggest to us who its inhabitants are. Nothing special happens. From inside the house one hears the wind moving the foliage and the sounds of farm birds mixed with noises produced by domestic chores. The water falling softly in the basin of the laundry sink.
          </p>
        </div>

        <aside class="work-page__ficha">
          <h4>TECHNICAL SHEET</h4>
          <div class="ficha">
            <strong>La travesia</strong><br>
            2017–2024<br><br>
            Installation.<br>
            Used and discarded wooden doors from family homes and mirror.<br><br>
            2.40 x 15 x 1.80 m
          </div>

          <h4 style="margin-top: var(--s3);">EXHIBITIONS</h4>
          <div class="ficha">
            Encuentros en la fabrica de polvo — MAMU, Bogota, 2024<br>
            Section "Ante el tiempo" [Before Time]
          </div>

          <h4 style="margin-top: var(--s3);">HOW TO CITE</h4>
          <div class="ficha" style="font-size: 0.65rem;">
            Escallon, M.E. (2017–2024). <em>La travesia</em>.
            Installation. Available at:
            mariaelviraescallon.com/en/works/la-travesia/
          </div>
        </aside>
      </div>

    </div>
  </article>

</Layout>
